Given an integer array nums, return true if any value appears at least twice in the array, and return false if every element is distinct.
var containsDuplicate = function(nums) {
return nums.length !== new Set(nums).size;
};
Explanation:
Given nums = [1, 2, 3, 1], the array length is 4. When we create a Set using new Set(nums), duplicate values are automatically removed, resulting in {1, 2, 3}. The size of this Set is 3. Although an array and a Set cannot be compared directly because they are different object types, we are not comparing the array to the Set itself. Instead, we compare nums.length (the total number of elements in the array) with new Set(nums).size (the number of unique elements in the Set). Since 4 !== 3, it means duplicate values were removed while creating the Set, so the expression evaluates to true.
Time & Space Complexity

• Time: O(n) — creating a Set visits each element once.

• Space: O(n) — in the worst case (all unique), the Set stores all n elements.
